Prostate cancer is one of the most common malignant tumors in males, remains one of the leading  causes of cancer-related deaths worldwide (Siegel et al. 2017). Over 80% of the metastatic prostate  cancer patients, the disease progresses within 12 to 18 months to an androgen-independent disease  (HRPC) and becomes incurable in the advanced stages (Clarke 2006). In the majority of prostate  tumors, the phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase (PI3K)/serine/threonine protein kinase B (Akt) pathway  is constitutively up-regulated due to the deletion of the tumor suppressor PTEN (Lawlor and Alessi  2001; Clarke 2006; Courtney et al. 2010). The PI3K/Akt/mTOR pathway is an important survival  pathway in regulating cell growth and adhesion, particularly during cancer progression, metastasis  and  drug  resistance.  The  central  role  of  this  pathway  in  resistance  to  chemotherapy  makes  this  pathway an attractive pharmacological target (Lawlor and Alessi 2001; Courtney et al. 2010; Bitting  and  Armstrong  2013).  Although  novel  therapeutic  agents  with  different  mechanisms  such  as  cabazitaxel  and  abiraterone  have  provided  clinical  benefit  to  prostate  cancer  patients,  the  overall  survival  of  these  patients  remains  poor.  Therefore,  finding  novel  agents  are  urgently  needed  to  inhibit cell growth and induce one or more cell death pathways in hormone- and chemotherapy-  refractory prostate cancer cells. Apoptosis and autophagy are two main mechanisms of chemotherapy-induced cell death having  multiple common molecular switches (Ricci and Zong 2001). ABSTRACT Liquidambar orientalis Mill: . (LOM), is an endemic species having a local  distribution in the southwestern coastal district of Turkey. Styrax liquidus  gum (SLG), is a gum-like resinous which exudates in response to injury of  the  trunk  of  LOM.  The  aim  of  the  study  was  to  investigate  the  cytotoxic  effects  and  the  molecular  mechanisms  of  the  ethanolic  SLG  extract  in  human  prostate  cancer  cells.  GC-MS  analysis  was  performed  to  identify  the volatile compound composition. Cytotoxicity was determined by XTT  analysis.  Apoptosis  and  necrosis  were  evaluated  via  ELISA  assay.  Autophagic  cell  death  was  detected  via  monodansylcadaverine  (MDC)  staining and by measuring the levels of LC3I and LC3II. The protein levels  of p-PI3K, p-Akt and p-mTOR were evaluated by western blot analysis. In  is  shown  that  the  SLG  extract  containing  the  present  study,  a  considerable  amount  of  ravidomycin  derivate  induced  autophagic  cell  death in prostate cancer cells via inhibiting the PI3K/Akt/mTOR pathway. harika.atmaca@cbu.edu.tr  Section of Molecular Biology, Department of Biology, Faculty of  ARTICLE HISTORY  Received 29 January 2020   Accepted 28 August 2020  KEYWORDS  Liquidambar  orientalis  Mill.;  cytotoxicity; autophagy;  ravidomycin; PI3K; prostate  cancer condensation, cellular fragmentation, plasma membrane blebbing and apoptotic body formation.  The  presence  of  acidic  vascular  organelles  in  the  cell  cytoplasm  that  leads  to  disruption  of  cytoplasmic  organelles  followed  by  nuclear  collapse  is  the  main  feature  of  autophagy.  However,  current knowledge of the cellular decision-making process between autophagy and apoptosis is still  unknown.

Liquidambar  orientalis  Mill.  (LOM),  is  an  endemic  species  belonging  to  the  Hamamelidaceae  family, has a local distribution in the southwestern coastal district of Turkey, especially in Koycegiz,  Fethiye, Marmaris and Ula (Karadeniz et al. 2013). The various parts of LOM have been used for  medicinal purposes such as stomach ulcers, burns, against parasitic infections, as antiseptic or as an  expectorant in Turkish folk medicine (Honda et al. 1996; Duru et al. 2002; Sağdıc et al. 2005). Styrax  liquidus (SL), is a gum-like resinous which exudates in response to injury of the trunk and becomes  gum  after  it  is  dried  (SLG)  (Karadeniz  et  al.  2013).  Although  the  antibacterial,  anti-ulcerogenic,  antioxidant and cytotoxic effects of this endemic species are studied previously, the cytotoxic effects  of SLG extract on human prostate cancer cells were not studied before. The aim of the study was to  investigate  the  cytotoxic  effects  of  SLG  extract  and  its  molecular  mechanisms  in  human  prostate  cancer cells. The gum was purchased from a local market in Köyceğiz-Muğla/Turkey on August 2018 and kept at  room temperature until used. Dried powder (10 g) of the  gum was  extracted in absolute ethanol  (EtOH)  at  room  temperature  and  ultrasonically  extracted  for  30  min,  and  then  cooled  at  room  temperature. The ethanolic extract was concentrated under reduced pressure by a rotary evaporator  to afford a viscous material. The viscous extract was then dissolved in 10 ml MeOH and stored at 4°  C. The final dilutions were made immediately before use and new stock solutions were prepared  before all experiments. The EtOH concentration (0.1%) was not cytotoxic to the cells. Gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC-MS)  analysis

GC-MS analysis of the extract was performed using an Agilent Technologies 7890A gas chromato- graphy  (GC)  system  hyphenated  to  a  5975  C  mass  spectrometer  (MS)  operated  in  the  electron-  ionization  (EI)  mode.  The  EtOH  extract  was  centrifuged  at  15,000  rpm  for  10  min,  and  the  supernatants  were  transferred  to  an  autosampler  vial  for  GC-MS  analysis.  MS  were  recorded  at  70 eV ionization energy in full scan mode in the 35–550 amu range. The ionization source and the  transfer line temperatures were  set at  230 and 290°C,  respectively. The  chromatographic column  was an Agilent HP-5 MS capillary column (30 m x 0.25 mm i.d., 0.25 µm film thickness). The oven  was held at an initial temperature of 40°C for 2 min, then heated to 300°C at 5°C min−1 and held for  16 min. The carrier gas was helium, at a flow rate of 1 mL min−1 and injector temperature was set as  220°C. In this case, 1.0 µL of the extract was injected in split mode (200:1). Interpretation of the  mass  spectrum  of  GC-MS  was  conducted  using  the  database  of  National  Institute  Standard  and  Technology (NIST).

WI-38  normal  embryonic  lung  fibroblasts  (ATCC  catalog  CCL-75)  were  obtained  from  ATCC,  USA.  WI-38  cells  were  maintained  in  Dulbecco’s  modified  Eagle  culture  medium  (DMEM),  supplemented with 0.01% sodium pyruvate and 10% FBS (Sigma Aldrich, USA). Human prostate  cancer cell lines PC-3 and DU-145 were obtained from Interlab Cell Line Collection (Genova, Italy).  Both  prostate  cancer  cells  were  cultured  in  RPMI  1640  supplemented  with  10%  heat-inactivated  fetal  bovine  serum,  1%  L-glutamine,  and  1%  penicillin-streptomycin.  All  of  the  cell  lines  were  maintained at 37°C in a humidified atmosphere with 5% CO2. XTT cell viability  assay First, we investigated the effect of SLG extract on the viability of human cell lines. Cells were seeded  at 1 × 104  cells/well in a final volume of 100 μl in 96-well flat-bottom microtiter plates. Then cells  were treated with the increasing concentrations of the gum extract (10–100 µM) for 24, 48 and 72 h,  and at the end of incubation, 100 μl of XTT (2,3-bis (2-methoxy-4-nitro-5-sulfophenyl)-5-[(phe- nylamino)carbonyl]-2  H-tetrazolium  hydroxide)  (Roche  Applied  Science,  Mannheim,  Germany)  was  added  to  each  well.  After  4  h  incubation  at  37◦C,  the  absorbance  was  measured  at  450  nm  against a reference wavelength at 650 nm using a microplate reader DTX880 Multimode Reader,  Beckman Coulter, Miami, FL, USA). Evaluation of apoptosis and necrosis

Induction  of  necrotic  and/or  apoptotic  cell  death  by  SLG  extract  was  evaluated  by  Cell  Death  Detection ELISA Plus Kit (Roche Applied Science, Mannheim, Germany) according to the instruc- tion’s manual (Atmaca et al. 2017). This kit evaluates the necrotic cell death from the supernatants  of  the  cells  and  determines  the  apoptotic  cell  death  by  the  detection  of  DNA  fragments  in  the  cytoplasm of apoptotic cells. Autophagic  cell  death  was  evaluated  by  monodansylcadaverine  (MDC)  staining.  MDC  is  a fluorescent dye that stains autophagic vacuoles. 1 × 105  cells were seeded on 24 well plates and  incubated at 37°C for 24 h for attachment. After attachment, cells were treated with the IC50 values  of SLG for 72 h. Then, cells were treated with 0.5 mM MDC and incubated for 10 min at 37°C. After  incubation,  cells  were  washed  four  times  with  PBS  and  immediately  analyzed  by  fluorescence  microscopy  using  an  inverted  microscope  (Olympus  BX51,  Tokyo,  Japan)  equipped  with  a  filter  system (excitation filter V-2A, 380–420 nm; barrier filter, 450 nm).

Protein  isolation  and  Western  blotting  have  been  described  before  (Atmaca  et  al.  2013).  The  primary antibodies for Western Blot were anti-LC3 (1:750; Cell Signaling, San Jose, CA, USA), anti-  phosphorylated  PI3K  (p-PI3K,  1:1000;  Cell  Signaling),  anti-  phosphorylated  Akt  (1:1000;  Cell  Signaling),  anti-phosphorylated  mTOR  (p-mTOR,  1:1000;  Cell  Signaling),  and  anti-β-actin  (1:1000;  Cell  Signaling).  The  secondary  antibodies  were  HRP-conjugated  anti-rabbit  antibodies  (1:500;  Cell  Signaling).  The  protein  bands  recognized  by  the  antibodies  were  visualized  by  the  Kodak Gel Logic 1500 Imaging System and quantified via Image J software (National Institutes of  Health, Bethesda, USA). All statistical analyses and graphs were performed with Graphpad Prism 5.0 software (La Jolla, CA,  USA).  IC50  values  were  calculated  via  Biosoft  CalcuSyn  2.1  software  (Ferguson,  MO,  USA).  Experiments  were  carried  out  in  triplicate  and  results  were  presented  as  the  means  ±  S.D.  The  difference  between  the  two  groups  was  analyzed  by  a  two-tailed  Student’s  test,  and  that  between  three or more groups were analyzed using one-way analysis of variance test (ANOVA) followed by  Dunnett’s t-test (Atmaca et al. 2020). p < 0.05 were considered as statistically significant. INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH RESEARCH The SLG extract inhibits the viability of human prostate cancer cells

The SLG produced by injuring Liquidambar orientalis Mill. is used against wounds, burns, peptic  ulcers, nocturnal enuresis, against parasitic infections, as antiseptic or as an expectorant in Anatolia  (Yeşilada et al. 1993; Sağdıc et al. 2005; Ugurlu and Secmen 2008). It has shown to have antibacterial  antifungal, genotoxic, and cytotoxic activities (Sağdıc et al. 2005; Karadeniz et al. 2013). However, to  the best of our knowledge, the effect of the SLG extract has not been investigated for its cytotoxic  activity on cancer cells. To evaluate the effect of SLG extract on human prostate cancer cells, PC-3  and DU-145 cells were treated with increasing concentrations of the extract (10–80 µg/mL) for 24,  48, 72 h and then XTT assay was performed. As shown in Figure 1(a,b), the SLG extract inhibited  the viability of both human prostate cancer cells in a time and concentration-dependent manner at  low concentrations, reaching the maximum cytotoxic activity at 72 h of treatment. The IC50 values  of  SLG extract  were  37.8  µg/mL  and  25.9  µg/mL in  PC-3  and  DU-145  cells at  72  h, respectively.  Effect of SLG extract on the viability of WI-38 normal embryonic lung fibroblasts was also evaluated  to test the possible impairing effect of the extract on human normal cells. The SLG extract was not  cytotoxic to normal cells at 24 h, but the extract slightly induced cytotoxicity on human normal cells  at 72 h (Figure 1(c)). The IC50 values of the SLG extract on human normal cells were higher than the  cancerous cells (IC50 value: 135 µg/mL in WI-38 cells at 72 h), indicating that prostate cancer cells  were more sensitive to the  SLG extract  than normal cells. Although many agents are used in the  treatment  of  prostate  cancer,  drug  resistance  and  dose-limiting  toxicities  limit  their  usage.  Therefore, there is an urgent need for novel agents with improved efficacy against prostate cancer

Volatile compound composition of SLG extract By the fact volatile compound composition may have different quality and quantity under different  geographical  and  environmental  conditions;  firstly  the  volatile  compound  composition  of  SLG  extract was determined via GC-MS analysis. The relative percentage amount of each compound was  calculated by comparing its average peak area to the total areas. In the literature, there are several  phytochemical  studies  investigating  the  presence  of  various  volatile  compounds  in  the  SL  (Hafızoglu  1982;  Fernandez  2005).  Fernandez  et  al.  showed  that  the  major  components  of  the  Asian storax were styrene (70.4%), α-pinene (19%) and β-caryophyllene (0.2%) (Fernandez 2005).  According  to  the  study  of  Hafizoglu  et  al.,  the  SL  extract  contains  styrene  (0.5%),  phenyl  propyl  alcohol  (0.5%),  cinnamyl  alcohol  (2.0%),  cinnamic  acid  (4.0%),  phenyl  propyl  cinnamate  (7.5%),  styracin (21.0, %) and some unidentified compounds. However, results of our study revealed that  the composition of the SLG was quite different from the SL. Moreover,  the  period  of  development,  climate,  environment,  topographic conditions, age and genetic structure of the plant affects the volatile compound content  (Skoula et al. 2000) The SLG extract does not induce apoptosis or  necrosis Cytotoxic  agents  can  induce  either  autophagy  or  apoptosis,  depending  on  cell  type,  time  and  concentration  of  the  agent.  But  it  is  unclear  how  cells  ‘assess’  cellular  damage  and  make  a  ‘life’  or  ‘death’  decision  upon  activating  autophagy  or  apoptosis  (Eisenberg-Lerner  et  al.  2009).  Autophagy occurs  at  a  low basal level  in  cells to  maintain homeostasis.  However, in  unfavorable  conditions  such  as  nutrient  deprivation,  oxidative  stress,  or  infection,  autophagic  cell  death  will  occur  (Gozuacik  and  Kimchi  2004).

To  understand  the  mechanism  of  the  cytotoxicity  induced  by  the  SLG  extract  in  human  prostate  cancer  cells,  we  evaluated  both  apoptotic  and  necrotic  cell  death.  There  were  no  necrotic  cells  or  fragmented  DNA  after  the  extract  treatment  at  72  h  which  was  the  highest  cytotoxic time point (10–80 µg/mL) (Figure  2). Therefore, it was  concluded that the SLG extract  treatment  did  not  induce  apoptosis  or  necrosis  in  human  PC-3  and  DU-145  prostate  cancer  cells.  These  results  indicated  that  some  other  death  mechanism  was  initiated  in  human  prostate  cancer  cells. Autophagic cell death was induced by the SLG extract To investigate the autophagic cell death, prostate cancer cells were stained with MDC, a fluorescent  compound that labels autophagic vacuoles. Autophagic vacuoles which are the distinct morpholo- gical markers of autophagy were observed in the cytoplasm of the SLG extract-treated cells after 72   h through MDC staining (Figure 3(a)). During  autophagy,  cytosolic  microtubule-associated  protein  1  light  chain  3β  (MAP1LC3B  or  LC3B)  I  is  converted  to  LC3B-II  by  a  ubiquitin-like  system  (Mizushima  et  al.  2001).  To  confirm  the  induction  of  autophagic  cell  death,  we  performed  a  western  blot  analysis  of  some  key  proteins  involved  in  autophagy.  The  levels  of  LC3I  and  LC3II  in  the  extract-treated  cells  were  evaluated  and  it  was  found  that  LC3II  levels  were  markedly  increased  in  the  extract-  treated  group  at  72  h  (Figure  3(b)).  These  findings  suggested  that  the  SLG  extract  induces  autophagy  in  prostate  cancer  cells. The SLG extract induces autophagy via the inhibition of the PI3K/Akt  pathway

The  signaling  pathways  involved  in  autophagy  are  complicated  and  include  the  PI3K/Akt/  mTOR  pathway  that  inhibits  autophagy  (Shao  et  al.  2016).  Thus,  we  investigated  this  pathway  in  prostate  cancer  cells  to  explore  the  molecular  mechanism  underlying  the  autophagic  cell  death  induced  by  the  SLG  extract.  The  results  demonstrated  decreased  levels  of  PI3K  in  both  prostate  cancer  cells  treated  with  the  IC50  values  of  SLG  for  72  h  (Figure  4).  Akt  is  a  down- stream  effector  of  PI3K  that  can  stimulate  the  mTOR  to  regulate  autophagy  negatively.  We  thus  investigated  whether  SLG-induced  autophagy  occurred  through  the  mammalian  target  of  rapamycin  (mTOR)  inhibition  because  mTOR  acts  as  a  well-conserved  and  central  regulator  in  autophagy  induction-and  AKT  modulates  mTOR  activation.  Western  blot  analysis  revealed  significantly  decreased  levels  of  PI3K,  p-Akt,  p-mTOR  and  increased  levels  of  LC3-II  in  SLG-  treated  cells,  indicating  that  the  PI3K/Akt  pathway  may  be  involved  in  the  regulation  of  autophagy  by  SLG  (Figure  4). Induction of autophagic cell death can represent a tool for targeting tumor cells, particularly when  resistance to classic apoptosis occurs. Autophagy can thus provide a useful method to limit tumor  progression and enhance the efficacy of anti-cancer treatments. In the present study, we have shown  that the SLG extract containing a considerable amount of ravidomycin derivate, induces autophagic  cell  death  in  prostate  cancer  cells  via  inhibiting  the  PI3K/Akt/mTOR  pathway.  Results  from  this  study may contribute to the development of novel ravidomycin derivates that may serve as a strong  potential drug for the treatment of prostate cancer.
